      <h2>How We Chose These Chairs</h2>
      <p>Every gaming chair on this list was evaluated on six core criteria:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Comfort:</strong> Foam density, seat cushion feel, and how the chair performs during 4+ hour sessions. We tested both immediate comfort and long-term break-in behavior.</li>
        <li><strong>Ergonomics:</strong> Lumbar support quality, adjustability range, and how well the chair promotes neutral spine alignment. Integrated lumbar systems scored higher than external pillows.</li>
        <li><strong>Build Quality:</strong> Frame materials, gas lift rating, caster quality, and overall construction. We checked for wobble, creaking, and material degradation over time.</li>
        <li><strong>Adjustability:</strong> Armrest dimensions, recline range, seat height range, and tilt mechanisms. More adjustment points mean you can dial in a better fit for your body.</li>
        <li><strong>Material & Durability:</strong> Upholstery quality, foam resilience, and how well the chair holds up after months of daily use. Cold-cure foam and quality fabrics scored highest.</li>
        <li><strong>Value:</strong> Performance relative to price. A $250 chair that matches $400 competitors scores higher than a $500 chair with marginal improvements over the $400 tier.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Gaming Chair Buying Guide</h2>

      <h3>Lumbar Support: Integrated vs. External Pillow</h3>
      <p>Integrated lumbar support (built into the backrest) is always better than an external pillow. Pillows shift when you move, lose shape over time, and don't provide consistent pressure. The Secretlab Titan Evo's 4-way magnetic lumbar, Razer Iskur V2's powered 6-point system, and Mavix M9's dynamic auto-adjusting lumbar are the best implementations on this list. If you're spending over $300, don't settle for a pillow.</p>

      <h3>Material Types: Leather vs. Fabric vs. Mesh</h3>
      <p>PU and PVC leather look great new but trap heat and can peel or crack within 2-3 years. Higher-quality PU (like Secretlab's NEO Hybrid Leatherette) lasts longer but still runs warmer than fabric. Fabric upholstery (Secretlab SoftWeave, Corsair fabric) breathes better, resists wear, and is more forgiving with spills if treated. Full mesh (DXRacer Air) is the coolest option but sacrifices cushioning. For most people in moderate climates, fabric or hybrid leatherette is the best compromise.</p>

      <h3>Weight Capacity: Why Headroom Matters</h3>
      <p>Never buy a chair where your body weight is close to the rated capacity. Operating near the limit compresses foam faster, stresses the gas lift cylinder, and shortens the chair's lifespan. Aim for at least 50 lbs of headroom. If you weigh over 250 lbs, look at the AndaSeat Kaiser 3 (395 lbs), Cougar Armor Titan Pro (370 lbs), or noblechairs Hero (330 lbs).</p>

      <h3>Adjustability: What Actually Matters</h3>
      <p>Not all adjustments are equally important. In priority order: seat height (everyone needs this), lumbar support depth, armrest height, recline angle, armrest width, seat depth, armrest depth, and armrest pivot. 4D armrests cover the four most important arm adjustments. The Autonomous ErgoChair Pro+ adds a fifth (rotation), but height and width matter most for reducing shoulder strain.</p>

